<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-452-929  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 452 929.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 17 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple licenses Truetype to Bitstream. (Truetype outline fonttechnology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (licenses)Bitstream Inc. (licenses).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     FontsLicensingOEMsCharacter GraphicsBit-Mapped Graphics.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>APPLE LICENSES TRUETYPE TO BITSTREAM CUPERTINO, CALIFORNIA, U.S.A., 1990 JUL12 (NB) -- Apple Computer is giving Bitstream the rights to license Apple'sTruetype outline font technology to Bitstream's original equipmentmanufacturers (OEMs).andP;  Although this technology isn't available to the publicyet, products incorporating it should appear late this year.andM;Outline fonts are mathematically descriptions of characters.andP;  Today AppleComputers use bitmapped fonts -- small collections of pixels that create thetext you see on screen.andP;  Since bitmapped fonts must be installed in each fontsize and style, they must be installed individually and they take up a lot ofroom on a hard disk.andP;  The newest fonts will be called outlined fonts.andO;Outline fonts store individual characters as a series of lines and curvesrather than a group of pixels.andP;  When an application asks for a character in asize, the Mac enlarges the size and fills in the display or outputs to aprinter without having to access a different file for each individualtypeface size and style.andM;Apple signed a similar licensing agreement with Microsoft in September, 1989.andM;Jim  Stoneham, Apple TrueType product manager, says of the deal: &quot;Apple'sgoal in licensing TrueType to both Microsoft and Bitstream is to extend thereach of native TrueType support in the printing and imaging products used inthe personal computer market.&quot;andM;TrueType will be offered to all new and existing Macintosh customers whenSystem 7.0 software is released, now expected at the end of the year.andM;Apple expects to see a large number of new fonts and applications that willtake advantage of this technology when TrueType ships with Macintosh SystemSoftware 7.0.andM;(Wendy Woods/19900713/Press ContactL Patty Tulloch, Apple Computer Inc.,andO;408/974-5449)</TEXT></DOC>